INSERT INTO `projects` VALUES ('bed2fd2f-7387-4949-82c1-d3a1fc2a53ce','NASA Space Challenge','Include interesting topics which are jargon heavy, but make the questions in such a way that they are very easy to understand.','101','2025-10-06 12:22:30');
INSERT INTO `question_option_variants` VALUES ('05b2f6b0-07ea-4a19-ba6b-286792e654ae','6d398556-e957-4903-92ea-e56cadfe1ee7','easy','[\"exception\", \"caughtException\", \"argumentError\", \"invalidArgument\"]','[3]','This is an easy-level question testing a fundamental naming convention: choosing a clear, context-specific variable name. The distractors represent common but suboptimal choices (a generic type name, redundant context information, or inconsistent terminology), while “invalidArgument” directly leverages surrounding context without unnecessary redundancy.','2025-10-01 11:29:01','2025-10-01 11:29:01');
INSERT INTO `question_option_variants` VALUES ('0e66eeda-fd51-41a4-90c8-814b665f9914','61de5f66-97e6-4fbf-ac89-062f30c51149','hard','[\"e\", \"argumentError\", \"exArg\", \"invalidArgument\"]','[3]','Hard: requires understanding nuanced naming conventions for catch parameters—avoiding redundancy with exception types (exArg), vagueness (e), or mismatched suffixes (argumentError)—and choosing a clear, concise name that describes the issue without repeating the type (invalidArgument).','2025-10-06 16:42:54','2025-10-06 16:42:54');
INSERT INTO `question_option_variants` VALUES ('0e8076d4-6789-4831-a28a-07777f485bdf','7ccaae52-f748-4edf-ad77-d2192139adf1','easy','[\"if n == 0: return 1\", \"def factorial(n):\", \"n * factorial(n - 1)\", \"factorial(n - 1)\"]','[0]','This is an easy question testing direct recall of a recursive base case. Distractors represent common fundamental misconceptions: confusing the function signature, the recursive multiplication step, or the bare recursive call with the actual base case condition and return.','2025-10-06 17:38:09','2025-10-06 17:38:09');
INSERT INTO `question_option_variants` VALUES ('17bf9ad8-48b7-49e1-8e7f-63ef4fc60254','113fa4a1-f16f-4004-9df3-b32cc55bb33b','easy','[\"shadow() returns 10.\", \"The global variable count remains 5 after calling shadow().\", \"modify() both updates the global count to 8 and returns 8.\", \"modify() returns 8 but does not change the global count.\"]','[0, 1, 2]','This question tests fundamental understanding of Python variable scope and the global keyword. At the easy level, learners must recall that assignments inside a function without ‘global’ create a new local variable (shadow()), while using ‘global’ in modify() affects the module-level variable. The distractor reflects a common misconception that return values alone affect globals.','2025-10-07 15:13:32','2025-10-07 15:13:32');
INSERT INTO `question_option_variants` VALUES ('1e8e11eb-a529-4442-aa93-fb2ba9174516','6d398556-e957-4903-92ea-e56cadfe1ee7','hard','[\"inversionError\", \"e\", \"matrixError\", \"invalidArgument\"]','[3]','At a hard difficulty level, the distractors require the student to deeply analyze the trade-offs of different naming strategies. “e” is a common but overly generic identifier, “inversionError” focuses on the operation rather than the specific invalid argument, and “matrixError” is ambiguous. Only “invalidArgument” succinctly leverages the context to name what actually went wrong without redundancy.','2025-10-01 11:29:01','2025-10-01 11:29:01');
INSERT INTO `question_option_variants` VALUES ('263d8e64-5d5b-45b6-95c0-2fae3dfa6d0c','6f9d98b2-c98f-4d26-bfbc-cf03a8fc8667','easy','[\"O(n)\", \"O(n^2)\", \"O(n log n)\", \"O(2^n)\"]','[3]','At an easy level, the question tests direct recall that the naive recursive Fibonacci implementation makes on the order of two calls per level for n levels, yielding exponential time O(2^n). The distractors reflect common simple mistakes—assuming linear (O(n)), quadratic (O(n^2)), or quasilinear (O(n log n)) behavior.','2025-10-06 17:39:13','2025-10-06 17:39:13');
INSERT INTO `question_option_variants` VALUES ('442732f6-c3b9-4a66-b026-f61bb505c2b7','64094e8a-2c9b-43e0-b28e-4dc151aa01fd','hard','[\"To visually group related variable assignments for improved readability\", \"To simplify version-control diffs by aligning change markers across lines\", \"To influence compiler memory-packing optimizations through uniform assignment alignment\", \"Because some linters require vertical operator alignment as part of style enforcement\"]','[0]','Distractors target deeper misconceptions: one about version-control diffs, one about compiler memory optimizations, and one about linting rules. Each requires multi-step reasoning to dismiss, matching a hard difficulty level.','2025-10-06 16:36:30','2025-10-06 16:36:30');
INSERT INTO `question_option_variants` VALUES ('468b95d0-b389-47f7-94d4-775b1a0aac0a','61de5f66-97e6-4fbf-ac89-062f30c51149','easy','[\"e\", \"ex\", \"argErr\", \"invalidArgument\"]','[3]','These distractors represent common but poor naming practices (single-letter abbreviations, generic exception names, unclear shorthand), while “invalidArgument” is the clear, descriptive choice. This question is categorized as easy because it tests a fundamental naming convention for exception parameters.','2025-10-06 16:42:54','2025-10-06 16:42:54');
INSERT INTO `question_option_variants` VALUES ('4d9a003a-2d01-4e07-939c-3301c614cf6e','7fb23849-df14-4e40-a5c3-2d059d62a9db','hard','[\"Bad code allows injecting file paths directly, so mocking is simpler\", \"They’re equally testable once file I/O is abstracted anyway\", \"Test complexity depends more on file size than code structure\", \"Good code is easier\"]','[3]','These distractors reflect deeper misconceptions about unit testing, mocking, and performance implications. They require the reader to analyze file I/O abstraction, dependency injection, and the relationship between file size and test complexity, making this a hard-level question.','2025-09-30 17:34:17','2025-09-30 17:34:17');
INSERT INTO `question_option_variants` VALUES ('51e27e6c-d337-441f-8a04-349adb76a968','181dba74-e09b-4b7d-be87-59a4ab54465c','hard','[\"Having dedicated feature folders (e.g., \'auth\', \'dashboard\'), each containing its related components, services, and tests.\", \"Separating code into \'presentation\', \'business\', and \'data-access\' directories, scattering each feature across multiple folders.\", \"Grouping code by development teams (e.g., \'TeamA\', \'TeamB\'), storing all layers and features under team-specific folders regardless of functionality.\", \"Arranging code under \'development\', \'staging\', and \'production\' directories, duplicating feature implementations across environment folders.\"]','[0]','These distractors require nuanced evaluation of folder-organization trade-offs absent in basic recall. They reflect deeper architectural misconceptions—layer-based scattering, team-based aggregation, environment-based duplication—demanding multi-step reasoning to discard, which aligns with a hard difficulty level.','2025-10-08 11:24:16','2025-10-08 11:24:16');
INSERT INTO `question_option_variants` VALUES ('5468c563-3857-4b37-9c3d-cfeb9370009f','181dba74-e09b-4b7d-be87-59a4ab54465c','medium','[\"Having dedicated feature folders (e.g., \'auth\', \'dashboard\'), each containing its related components, services, and tests.\", \"Grouping components, services, and utilities into top-level folders by type (e.g., \'components\', \'services\'), ignoring feature context.\", \"Centralizing all tests in a single \'tests\' directory and placing source code in generic folders by type, not by feature.\", \"Organizing directories based solely on file extensions (e.g., \'js\', \'css\'), mixing features indiscriminately.\"]','[0]','This question is medium difficulty because it asks learners to analyze and compare different folder organization strategies—feature-based versus layer-based or extension-based—and recognize why centralizing tests or grouping by file type/extension can impede clarity and scalability.','2025-10-08 11:24:16','2025-10-08 11:24:16');
INSERT INTO `question_option_variants` VALUES ('5911873d-6d5f-433c-907b-c3edf6854dba','6d398556-e957-4903-92ea-e56cadfe1ee7','medium','[\"ex\", \"matrixException\", \"invalidArgument\", \"error\"]','[2]','This set reflects a medium difficulty: candidates must analyze naming conventions and context to identify redundancy. “ex” is too terse and hides meaning; “matrixException” redundantly repeats what the surrounding context already conveys; “error” is overly generic. “invalidArgument” concisely describes the specific issue without duplicating contextual information, making it the best choice.','2025-10-01 11:29:01','2025-10-01 11:29:01');
INSERT INTO `question_option_variants` VALUES ('672e64f3-1423-4885-9d47-4430d0ad178e','7fb23849-df14-4e40-a5c3-2d059d62a9db','easy','[\"Bad code is easier\", \"Good code is easier\", \"Both are equally testable\", \"Testability varies with file size\"]','[1]','Difficulty: easy. This tests a fundamental concept—decoupling I/O from logic improves unit testing. Distractors reflect straightforward misconceptions (thinking direct file access is simpler to test, that both approaches are the same, or that testability depends on file size).','2025-09-30 17:34:17','2025-09-30 17:34:17');
INSERT INTO `question_option_variants` VALUES ('69803c54-8e00-463f-b866-e6255f54dd86','0863a3fb-f50a-47de-a624-511e11342ab3','medium','[\"def add_tag(post, tag): return {**post, \'tags\': post[\'tags\'] + [tag]}\", \"def add_tag(post, tag): post[\'tags\'].append(tag); return post\", \"def add_tag(post, tag): result = {**post}; result[\'tags\'] += [tag]; return result\", \"def add_tag(post, tag): post_copy = post.copy(); post_copy[\'tags\'].append(tag); return post_copy\"]','[0]','This question is medium difficulty because it requires understanding the difference between mutating the original data structure versus returning a new one, as well as how shallow copying (with dict.copy() or unpacking) still shares references to nested lists. The distractors target common mistakes: directly appending to the original list, using += on a shared list, and relying on a shallow dict.copy() to avoid mutation.','2025-10-08 13:21:28','2025-10-08 13:21:28');
INSERT INTO `question_option_variants` VALUES ('75174616-c433-41a7-944e-69fb1275c151','7fb23849-df14-4e40-a5c3-2d059d62a9db','medium','[\"Bad code is easier to test because it’s simpler\", \"Good code is easier\", \"Both snippets require mocking, so test difficulty is the same\", \"Testability depends on file encoding, not code structure\"]','[1]','This question is medium difficulty because it requires understanding how decoupling file I/O via dependency injection (using streams) makes unit testing easier, and distinguishing that from unrelated factors like file encoding or mere simplicity, as well as recognizing that both versions still involve I/O mocking if they directly open files.','2025-09-30 17:34:17','2025-09-30 17:34:17');
INSERT INTO `question_option_variants` VALUES ('75fa37ae-b861-44af-a1bb-31046c319f93','64094e8a-2c9b-43e0-b28e-4dc151aa01fd','easy','[\"To visually group related variable assignments for improved readability\", \"To satisfy strict code style checks in linters\", \"To improve runtime performance of assignment statements\", \"To prevent variable name collisions in larger codebases\"]','[0]','This question is at an easy level because it tests direct recall of a fundamental code readability practice. The distractors reflect common misconceptions about compiler enforcement, execution performance, and naming conflicts, which beginners might plausibly confuse with alignment benefits.','2025-10-06 16:36:30','2025-10-06 16:36:30');
INSERT INTO `question_option_variants` VALUES ('762411d6-2711-472f-bd60-a167bf3f6a80','64094e8a-2c9b-43e0-b28e-4dc151aa01fd','medium','[\"To visually group related variable assignments for improved readability\", \"To prepare the code for automated formatting by a code linter\", \"To make version control diffs cleaner by aligning edit markers\", \"To facilitate batch value updates using column-based text editor selection\"]','[0]','The distractors target realistic but incorrect reasons—formatter integration, VCS diff appearance, and editor tricks—requiring moderate analysis of tooling versus genuine readability goals, matching medium difficulty.','2025-10-06 16:36:30','2025-10-06 16:36:30');
INSERT INTO `question_option_variants` VALUES ('76cf9a3d-56bd-48d1-bba5-4c4deaece208','8eda6009-947f-43b6-99e5-534729eb0e29','easy','[\"1 3 (4, 5) 6 {\'d\': 7, \'e\': 8}\", \"1 3 (4, 5) 5 {\'d\': 7, \'e\': 8, \'c\': 6}\", \"1 2 (3, 4, 5) 6 {\'d\': 7, \'e\': 8}\", \"1 2 (3, 4, 5) 5 {\'d\': 7, \'e\': 8, \'c\': 6}\"]','[0]','Easy difficulty: the distractors target fundamental misconceptions about positional vs. default vs. keyword-only parameter binding in Python, requiring direct recall of how *args and keyword-only arguments are handled.','2025-10-07 14:06:49','2025-10-07 14:06:49');
INSERT INTO `question_option_variants` VALUES ('77536966-2285-4016-9fe2-966a02ae1755','49754497-933e-4bdd-bf0d-e84c0b11ccb6','easy','[\"Use a default parameter cutoff=0.8 in the function signature\", \"Prompt the user to input the cutoff value at runtime\", \"Read cutoff from an external configuration file at program startup\", \"Store cutoff as a class attribute in a helper class\"]','[2]','This is an easy-level question: it requires recognizing that reading configuration from an external file best removes a hard-coded “magic” value. The distractors reflect common but inferior approaches: default arguments still embed the value, prompting at runtime is manual, and class attributes keep the constant in code.','2025-10-06 15:28:14','2025-10-06 15:28:14');
INSERT INTO `question_option_variants` VALUES ('77a46974-70ba-4939-8f90-11ce0b7da0f8','e6d6d275-4822-495f-a2d5-e0d1aeb24e72','hard','[\"With Git, the developer can commit changes locally and view the entire history without a network; SVN requires a connection to commit and fetch history.\", \"Git needs to contact a remote to update remote-tracking refs before showing logs for branches you haven’t fetched, whereas SVN stores all fetched logs locally for offline review.\", \"SVN lets you diff against any revision you’ve updated locally offline, but Git requires you to push commits before git diff can compare against earlier history.\", \"Git merge operations rely on remote merge-base lookup and can’t run entirely offline; SVN supports offline merges between branches.\"]','[0]','These distractors require nuanced understanding of Git’s local vs remote-tracking refs, diffing mechanics, and merge-base calculation, making the question hard by targeting realistic yet deeper misconceptions about DVCS versus centralized workflows.','2025-10-01 10:02:55','2025-10-01 10:02:55');
INSERT INTO `question_option_variants` VALUES ('80347e5e-cd9f-4b08-bb43-2159532cc764','65761676-577d-43a5-97d5-8e2b072732ba','hard','[\"Define alpha = 0.05 and use if statistic > alpha\", \"Define CRITICAL_VALUE = 3.841 and use if statistic > CRITICAL_VALUE\", \"Define CHI_95TH_PERCENTILE = 3.841 and use if statistic > CHI_95TH_PERCENTILE\", \"Define chi_square_05 = 3.841 and use if statistic > chi_square_05\"]','[3]','This question is rated hard because the distractors require deep understanding of statistical testing: confusing p-value thresholds (alpha) with test-statistic cutoffs, using overly generic or ambiguous naming, and recognizing the precise notation for a chi-square 95% critical value at α=0.05. Selecting the correct answer demands multi-step reasoning about naming conventions, distribution percentiles, and the distinction between α and the critical value.','2025-10-01 11:28:14','2025-10-01 11:28:14');
INSERT INTO `question_option_variants` VALUES ('81f94ad6-c33a-4b7d-a531-3d1f5ea59565','49754497-933e-4bdd-bf0d-e84c0b11ccb6','hard','[\"Use argparse to accept a --cutoff argument at program invocation and pass it directly to filter_data\", \"Fetch the cutoff value from an environment variable (e.g., os.environ) each time filter_data is called\", \"Read cutoff from an external configuration file at program startup\", \"Encapsulate filter_data in a class where the cutoff is a constructor parameter, requiring instantiation before filtering\"]','[2]','Hard difficulty: distractors require deep analysis of configuration strategies and their trade-offs. Each option reflects a realistic but flawed approach—CLI flags, environment coupling, or heavyweight OOP—forcing nuanced reasoning about best practices versus dynamic configuration.','2025-10-06 15:28:14','2025-10-06 15:28:14');
INSERT INTO `question_option_variants` VALUES ('83734edd-64a4-4f39-b25d-ce279a3dfd93','0863a3fb-f50a-47de-a624-511e11342ab3','hard','[\"def add_tag(post, tag): new_post = post.copy(); new_post[\'tags\'].append(tag); return new_post\", \"def add_tag(post, tag): return {**post, \'tags\': post[\'tags\'] + [tag]}\", \"def add_tag(post, tag): tags = post[\'tags\']; tags += [tag]; return {**post, \'tags\': tags}\", \"def add_tag(post, tag): return {**post, \'tags\': post[\'tags\'].append(tag) or post[\'tags\']}\"]','[1]','These options test nuanced Python behaviors: shallow vs. deep copying of dicts, how list append mutates in place and returns None, and how redundant or misplaced mutations can break immutability. Recognizing the only truly pure refactoring demands multi-step reasoning about nested data structures and return values, fitting a hard difficulty level.','2025-10-08 13:21:28','2025-10-08 13:21:28');
INSERT INTO `question_option_variants` VALUES ('8d7a961c-64f4-432e-a4cb-9b4377339cdf','61de5f66-97e6-4fbf-ac89-062f30c51149','medium','[\"exception\", \"argException\", \"invalidArgument\", \"argError\"]','[2]','These distractors reflect common naming mistakes at a medium difficulty level: \'exception\' is too generic, \'argException\' redundantly abbreviates yet still ambiguous, and \'argError\' mixes terms unhelpfully. \'invalidArgument\' is concise, specific, and avoids redundancy, following best practices.','2025-10-06 16:42:54','2025-10-06 16:42:54');
INSERT INTO `question_option_variants` VALUES ('938f6a2a-2273-4fed-8271-365a388e632e','8eda6009-947f-43b6-99e5-534729eb0e29','hard','[\"1 3 (4, 5) 6 {\'d\': 7, \'e\': 8}\", \"1 3 (4, 5) 5 {\'c\': 6, \'d\': 7, \'e\': 8}\", \"1 3 (4, 5, 6) 5 {\'d\': 7, \'e\': 8}\", \"1 2 (3, 4, 5) 6 {\'d\': 7, \'e\': 8}\"]','[0]','This question demands a precise, multi-step analysis of Python’s argument-binding mechanics: distinguishing positional vs. keyword arguments, the placement of *args vs. keyword-only parameters (c=5), and **kwargs. The distractors target common deep errors (misplacing c, mispopulating args, or ignoring the explicit override of b), ensuring a high difficulty level.','2025-10-07 14:06:49','2025-10-07 14:06:49');
INSERT INTO `question_option_variants` VALUES ('a1ea9cd0-bf75-4394-8615-48b604fd8e41','113fa4a1-f16f-4004-9df3-b32cc55bb33b','hard','[\"shadow() returns 10.\", \"The global variable count remains 5 after calling shadow().\", \"modify() both updates the global count to 8 and returns 8.\", \"shadow() reassigns the global count to 10, causing the prints to be 10, 10, 13, and 13.\"]','[0, 1, 2]','This question requires in-depth understanding of Python’s variable scope rules, the use of the global keyword, and the order of execution across multiple function calls. The distractor combines multiple misconceptions—namely that a local assignment without a global declaration modifies the global state and how that feeds into subsequent calls—making it a realistic but incorrect multi-step reasoning trap appropriate for a hard difficulty level.','2025-10-07 15:13:32','2025-10-07 15:13:32');
INSERT INTO `question_option_variants` VALUES ('af067152-dc33-4013-a63b-f7909b21c7dc','e6d6d275-4822-495f-a2d5-e0d1aeb24e72','easy','[\"With Git, the developer can commit changes locally and view the entire history without a network; SVN requires a connection to commit and fetch history.\", \"Git won\'t let you inspect diffs offline; you must fetch from remote first.\", \"SVN automatically syncs all repository history locally, so network isn\'t required to see past changes.\", \"Git cannot create or switch branches without reaching the central repository.\"]','[0]','This set of options targets an easy difficulty by focusing on fundamental misconceptions about Git versus SVN in offline scenarios. The distractors are plausible but incorrect statements about offline capabilities, ensuring direct recall of the core difference without requiring deeper analysis.','2025-10-01 10:02:55','2025-10-01 10:02:55');
INSERT INTO `question_option_variants` VALUES ('b07a9f70-6abb-4c7f-a446-514565f6273b','6f9d98b2-c98f-4d26-bfbc-cf03a8fc8667','medium','[\"O(n log n)\", \"O(n^2)\", \"O(2^(n/2))\", \"O(2^n)\"]','[3]','At medium difficulty, students must set up and solve the recurrence T(n)=T(n-1)+T(n-2)+1. Common missteps include equating it to mergesort (n·log n), assuming double recursion gives quadratic (n²), or treating both subcalls as size n–2 to get 2^(n/2). The correct tight Big-O is exponential, O(2ⁿ).','2025-10-06 17:39:13','2025-10-06 17:39:13');
INSERT INTO `question_option_variants` VALUES ('b1941839-33e5-414d-8714-c8743f404a22','7ccaae52-f748-4edf-ad77-d2192139adf1','hard','[\"if n == 0: return 1\", \"else: return n * factorial(n - 1)\", \"return factorial(n - 1)\", \"def factorial(n):\"]','[0]','Hard difficulty: Students must distinguish the true base case from various parts of the recursive mechanism—the function declaration, the recursive call itself, and the recursive branch—requiring careful code analysis and preventing common deeper misconceptions about what actually stops the recursion.','2025-10-06 17:38:09','2025-10-06 17:38:09');
INSERT INTO `question_option_variants` VALUES ('b736f995-53f7-447d-b9bc-342477a4a0ba','113fa4a1-f16f-4004-9df3-b32cc55bb33b','medium','[\"shadow() returns 10.\", \"The global variable count remains 5 after calling shadow().\", \"modify() both updates the global count to 8 and returns 8.\", \"Functions in Python can modify global variables without a global declaration.\"]','[0, 1, 2]','This question targets medium difficulty by combining understanding of local versus global scope and the use of the global keyword. The distractor reflects the common misconception that functions can alter globals without declaring them.','2025-10-07 15:13:32','2025-10-07 15:13:32');
INSERT INTO `question_option_variants` VALUES ('c6031593-d711-41a9-a87f-3d5081e5e4e1','181dba74-e09b-4b7d-be87-59a4ab54465c','easy','[\"Having dedicated feature folders (e.g., \'auth\', \'dashboard\'), each containing its related components, services, and tests.\", \"Creating separate top-level directories for each file type (e.g., \'components\', \'services\', \'utils\') without regard to feature separation.\", \"Keeping all test files in one central \'tests\' folder, detached from their corresponding feature code.\", \"Grouping files based on their file extension or technology stack folders like \'js\', \'css\', \'images\' rather than by feature.\"]','[0]','This is an easy-level question requiring direct recall of fundamental folder organization principles: distinguishing feature-based grouping from grouping by file type or extension.','2025-10-08 11:24:16','2025-10-08 11:24:16');
INSERT INTO `question_option_variants` VALUES ('c6beba12-3a42-4f32-8ace-075420325b58','8eda6009-947f-43b6-99e5-534729eb0e29','medium','[\"1 3 (4, 5) 6 {\'d\': 7, \'e\': 8}\", \"1 3 (4, 5) 5 {\'d\': 7, \'e\': 8, \'c\': 6}\", \"1 2 (3, 4, 5) 6 {\'d\': 7, \'e\': 8}\", \"1 2 (3, 4, 5) 5 {\'d\': 7, \'e\': 8}\"]','[0]','These options target medium-level misconceptions: one distractor treats the keyword-only parameter c as still 5 with c=6 dumped into kwargs, others mix up using the default for b or c and misassign extra positionals to args. Understanding positional vs keyword-only binding, defaults, *args and **kwargs is required.','2025-10-07 14:06:49','2025-10-07 14:06:49');
INSERT INTO `question_option_variants` VALUES ('cf7e1699-55e6-4645-a248-4e4a9b66ae73','0863a3fb-f50a-47de-a624-511e11342ab3','easy','[\"def add_tag(post, tag): return {**post, \'tags\': post[\'tags\'] + [tag]}\", \"def add_tag(post, tag): new_post = post.copy(); new_post[\'tags\'].append(tag); return new_post\", \"def add_tag(post, tag): new_post = {**post}; new_post[\'tags\'] += [tag]; return new_post\", \"def add_tag(post, tag): tags = post[\'tags\'] + [tag]; return {\'tags\': tags}\"]','[0]','This is an easy-level question testing the core concept of pure functions and immutability in Python. The correct option uses dict unpacking to create a new object and a new list of tags, leaving the original input unchanged. Each distractor represents a common mistake: shallow copying but mutating the nested list, using dict unpack but still modifying the shared list, or omitting other post fields entirely.','2025-10-08 13:21:28','2025-10-08 13:21:28');
INSERT INTO `question_option_variants` VALUES ('d5f7722b-269a-46df-87b9-018b79115eba','65761676-577d-43a5-97d5-8e2b072732ba','medium','[\"Define DECISION_BOUNDARY = 3.841 and use if statistic > DECISION_BOUNDARY\", \"Define chi_square_05 = 3.841 and use if statistic > chi_square_05\", \"Define CVALUE = 3.841 and use if statistic > CVALUE\", \"Define CRITICAL_THRESHOLD = 3.841 and use if statistic > CRITICAL_THRESHOLD\"]','[1]','At medium difficulty, the student must recognize a clear, self-documenting constant name that conveys both the test (chi-square) and the significance level (0.05). The incorrect options use vague or generic names (DECISION_BOUNDARY, CVALUE, CRITICAL_THRESHOLD) that omit key context.','2025-10-01 11:28:14','2025-10-01 11:28:14');
INSERT INTO `question_option_variants` VALUES ('dccb677b-78b8-48b0-807d-8fab4e5e512d','6f9d98b2-c98f-4d26-bfbc-cf03a8fc8667','hard','[\"O(n)\", \"O(n^2)\", \"O(phi^n)\", \"O(2^n)\"]','[3]','At a hard level, students must analyze the recursion tree growth and distinguish between polynomial bounds, the precise exponential base φ ≈1.618 from Binet’s formula, and the looser O(2^n) bound. Distractors reflect common miscounts as linear or quadratic, and a subtler confusion with φ^n complexity.','2025-10-06 17:39:13','2025-10-06 17:39:13');
INSERT INTO `question_option_variants` VALUES ('dff1b9ec-1923-427a-8ebc-ce80fdf1b9f0','65761676-577d-43a5-97d5-8e2b072732ba','easy','[\"Define THRESHOLD = 3.841 and use if statistic > THRESHOLD\", \"Define chi_square_05 = 3.841 and use if statistic > chi_square_05\", \"Define SIGNIFICANCE_LEVEL = 3.841 and use if statistic > SIGNIFICANCE_LEVEL\", \"Define P_VALUE_THRESHOLD = 3.841 and use if statistic > P_VALUE_THRESHOLD\"]','[1]','These options reflect an easy-level task of choosing clear, descriptive constant names. The distractors show typical beginner mistakes—using a generic threshold name or confusing the critical chi-square value with a significance level or p-value threshold—while the correct option precisely encodes the test and confidence level (chi_square_05).','2025-10-01 11:28:14','2025-10-01 11:28:14');
INSERT INTO `question_option_variants` VALUES ('e1b9f1a8-bcd8-433a-ba59-7c8ae67fd40c','7ccaae52-f748-4edf-ad77-d2192139adf1','medium','[\"if n == 0: return 1\", \"return n * factorial(n - 1)\", \"return 1\", \"def factorial(n):\"]','[0]','Identifying the base case in a recursive function requires understanding that it’s both a specific condition and its associated return value, distinguishing it from the recursive step and other code elements like the function signature or a standalone return. This integration of control‐flow and recursion concepts makes the question medium difficulty.','2025-10-06 17:38:09','2025-10-06 17:38:09');
INSERT INTO `question_option_variants` VALUES ('ed7e4ea3-13cb-4daf-ab7b-5758a1a189cf','49754497-933e-4bdd-bf0d-e84c0b11ccb6','medium','[\"Define CUTOFF as a module-level constant at the top and import it where needed\", \"Use a default function parameter for cutoff in filter_data\", \"Keep the literal 0.8 inside filter_data but add a more descriptive docstring\", \"Read cutoff from an external configuration file at program startup\"]','[3]','Medium difficulty: requires understanding various refactoring approaches—module constants, default parameters, documentation vs. true dynamic configuration. Only reading from an external file fully removes hard-coding and supports runtime flexibility, while distractors reflect common but insufficient practices.','2025-10-06 15:28:14','2025-10-06 15:28:14');
INSERT INTO `question_option_variants` VALUES ('ffa04b83-c103-4f2f-acf7-d283f20dd830','e6d6d275-4822-495f-a2d5-e0d1aeb24e72','medium','[\"With Git, the developer can commit changes locally and view the entire history without a network; SVN requires a connection to commit and fetch history.\", \"SVN lets you create local branches without a server, but Git demands server connectivity for branch operations.\", \"Git only caches recent commits locally; older history must be fetched from the remote, whereas SVN stores the entire history in the working copy.\", \"SVN\'s working copy allows merging between branches offline, yet Git can only merge after retrieving branch data from the central repository.\"]','[0]','These distractors target common medium-level misconceptions about Git vs. SVN, each combining one or two flawed ideas: local branching requirements, history caching, and offline merge behavior. They’re plausible but inaccurate, requiring moderate analysis of DVCS vs. centralized workflows.','2025-10-01 10:02:55','2025-10-01 10:02:55');
INSERT INTO `questions` VALUES ('00dc5c95-7669-4737-be89-1a22a54a17b2','101','45f977b0-5088-4fb6-b4f7-a680e167e063','3dce6102-6fb1-4295-9cc1-c5066e8f1844','Which sequence of Git commands correctly stages changes, creates a snapshot, and then shows the status of your working directory?','[\"git status, git add, git commit\", \"git add, git commit, git status\", \"git commit, git add, git status\", \"git status, git commit, git add\"]','[1]','easy','[\"git\", \"staging\", \"commit\"]','rag_context',0,0,'2025-09-30 13:41:11','2025-09-30 13:41:11','mcq');
INSERT INTO `questions` VALUES ('033e9f7d-42c3-45b6-bf99-e8f23c5814b3','user-admin-001','1f9f921d-8a65-4a6e-9b74-96a6979da10b','8cceadf0-de0e-430d-a195-50d9d961ce79','Consider the following pseudocode snippets illustrating two GoF patterns:\n<pre><code>\n// Decorator\nclass Window:\n    def draw(self): pass\nclass ScrollDecorator(Window):\n    def draw(self):\n        self.addScrollBars()\n        super().draw()\n\n// Observer\nclass Subject:\n    def __init__(self): self.observers = []\n    def attach(self, o): self.observers.append(o)\n    def notifyAll(self):\n        for o in self.observers:\n            o.update()\n</code></pre>\nAlthough both patterns enable dynamic behavior extension, they belong to different GoF categories. Which of the following best explains why Decorator is classified as a Structural pattern while Observer is classified as a Behavioral pattern?','[\"Decorator modifies object composition (wrapping) to add responsibilities, affecting the system\'s static structure; Observer defines one-to-many communication between objects, affecting runtime interaction.\", \"Decorator uses inheritance to extend functionality across class hierarchies; Observer relies on composition to manage event distribution.\", \"Decorator applies to single object instances only; Observer applies at the class level, broadcasting to all instances.\", \"Decorator mandates modification of the wrapped object\'s interface; Observer transparently attaches to subjects without changing their API.\"]','[0]','hard','[\"Structural\", \"Behavioral\"]','https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Software_design_pattern',0,0,'2025-10-08 21:53:59','2025-10-08 21:53:59','mcq');
INSERT INTO `questions` VALUES ('03cea941-9d53-4795-9c6f-70b40a808ac7','101','22f22cb0-c592-491f-827b-4ef683b97cc1','23d58d77-91d2-49a0-83ea-dde75a5d6df8','Given the following code snippet:\n\n<pre><code>\nbubble_sort(data)\n</code></pre>\n\nWhich of the following comments best serves as a rationale-driven comment explaining the non-obvious choice of using bubble sort?','[\"// Sort the data\", \"// Bubble sort is preferred here because the list is almost sorted, making it faster than quicksort\", \"// Implements bubble sort algorithm\", \"// TODO: benchmark sorting algorithms\"]','[1]','easy','[\"comments\", \"rationale\"]','https://mitcommlab.mit.edu/broad/commkit/coding-mindset/',0,1,'2025-10-06 10:47:58','2025-10-06 10:47:58','mcq');
INSERT INTO `questions` VALUES ('04f559a2-6e5b-4789-b2d3-e6df3004d7b4','101','1ae3f056-2a49-4bff-9c8c-5fe084e2d83b','066c011c-a649-4957-a54d-1a7cd2d7d7f4','Identify the magic value in the bad snippet, and the improvement in the good snippet:\nBad code:\n<pre><code>def calculate_final_price(price):\n    return price * 1.075\n</code></pre>\nGood code:\n<pre><code>TAX_RATE = 0.075\n\ndef calculate_final_price(price):\n    return price * (1 + TAX_RATE)\n</code></pre>\nWhich statement is correct?','[\"The bad code uses a magic value 1.075; the good code defines a named constant\", \"The bad code is shorter and thus clearer\", \"The good code avoids using multiplication\", \"Both snippets are equally clear\"]','[0]','Medium','[\"Magic Values\", \"Constants\"]','Good Code, Bad Code -- Tom Long -- Anna’s Archive.pdf (chapter 6.1)“Avoid returning magic values”',0,0,'2025-09-16 11:20:01','2025-09-16 11:20:01','mcq');
INSERT INTO `questions` VALUES ('06588594-43d8-4193-98a6-8cc87b50f09f','101','1ae3f056-2a49-4bff-9c8c-5fe084e2d83b','066c011c-a649-4957-a54d-1a7cd2d7d7f4','Consider these two functions:\nBad code:\n<pre><code>def append_item(lst, item):\n    lst.append(item)\n    return lst\n</code></pre>\nGood code:\n<pre><code>def append_item(lst, item):\n    new_list = lst.copy()\n    new_list.append(item)\n    return new_list\n</code></pre>\nTrue or False: The good code avoids a hidden side effect on the caller’s list.','[\"True\", \"False\"]','[0]','Medium','[\"Side Effects\", \"Mutability\"]','Good Code, Bad Code -- Tom Long -- Anna’s Archive.pdf (chapter 6.3)“Avoid causing unexpected side effects”',0,0,'2025-09-16 11:20:01','2025-09-16 11:20:01','mcq');
INSERT INTO `questions` VALUES ('06fa5aa3-03e6-47ea-82e1-8acb2c3404fd','101','113bba62-604b-430b-a8e5-4605a157a318','066c011c-a649-4957-a54d-1a7cd2d7d7f4','What benefit does defining TextImportanceScorer as an interface provide in the following refactored code?  \nBad: class TextImportanceScorer { ... }  \nGood:  \n<pre><code>interface TextImportanceScorer {\n  Boolean isImportant(String text);\n}\n\nclass WordBasedScorer implements TextImportanceScorer { ... }\nclass ModelBasedScorer implements TextImportanceScorer { ... }\n</code></pre>','[\"Hides implementation details\", \"Prevents code reuse\", \"Increases compile-time errors\", \"Reduces modularity\"]','[0]','Medium','[\"Interfaces\", \"Abstraction\"]','Good Code, Bad Code -- Tom Long -- 1, 2021 -- Manning Publications -- Anna’s Archive.pdf',0,0,'2025-09-16 11:18:25','2025-09-16 11:18:25','mcq');
INSERT INTO `questions` VALUES ('0863a3fb-f50a-47de-a624-511e11342ab3','user-admin-001','87587b16-87be-44d5-b88e-8f0fb54f586b','6c68a915-6bd2-4a98-a9f0-6f76e55889d1','Consider the following function:\n<pre><code>\ndef add_tag(post, tag):\n    post[\'tags\'].append(tag)\n    return post\n</code></pre>\nWhich refactoring makes add_tag a pure function that preserves immutability?','[\"def add_tag(post, tag): return {**post, \'tags\': post[\'tags\'] + [tag]}\", \"def add_tag(post, tag): post[\'tags\'].append(tag); return post\", \"def add_tag(post, tag): post[\'tags\'] = post[\'tags\'] + [tag]; return post\", \"def add_tag(post, tag): new_post = post; new_post[\'tags\'] += [tag]; return new_post\"]','[0]','easy','[\"PureFunctions\", \"Immutability\"]','https://medium.com/geekculture/what-is-a-good-code-and-why-is-it-all-about-others-not-ourselves-40730c7a03e5',0,0,'2025-10-08 11:20:17','2025-10-08 11:20:17','mcq');
INSERT INTO `questions` VALUES ('093ba9f3-2379-4b97-96fa-927671c4f5ba','101','113bba62-604b-430b-a8e5-4605a157a318','066c011c-a649-4957-a54d-1a7cd2d7d7f4','Bad code:  \n<pre><code>HttpConnection connect(String url) {\n  // open socket, write HTTP, parse headers\n}\n</code></pre>Good code:  \n<pre><code>HttpConnection connection = HttpConnection.connect(\"http://example.com\");\n</code></pre>What is the main advantage of the good code?','[\"Layers of abstraction hide complexity\", \"Lower performance\", \"Harder to debug\", \"Increased dependencies\"]','[0]','Medium','[\"Abstraction\", \"Readability\"]','Good Code, Bad Code -- Tom Long -- 1, 2021 -- Manning Publications -- Anna’s Archive.pdf',0,0,'2025-09-16 11:18:25','2025-09-16 11:18:25','mcq');
INSERT INTO `questions` VALUES ('096ff1f0-a5e0-4a47-bf42-ca64b21b10c4','101','4982c0da-e4ec-4bb3-8724-e84f6e4994f4','23d58d77-91d2-49a0-83ea-dde75a5d6df8','Examine the following code snippet:\n<pre><code>\nclass CSVReader:\n    def read(self, path):\n        f = open(path, \'r\')\n        data = f.read()\n        f.close()\n        return data\n\nclass JSONReader:\n    def read(self, path):\n        f = open(path, \'r\')\n        data = f.read()\n        f.close()\n        return data\n</code></pre>\nWhich refactoring approach uses object-oriented modularization to remove the duplicated file-handling logic?','[\"Extract a standalone function read_file() and call it within each class.\", \"Create a common base class FileReader with the shared read() method and have CSVReader and JSONReader inherit from it.\", \"Use composition by defining a FileHandler helper class and instantiate it in both reader classes.\", \"Replace the classes with separate modules each containing its own read_file() function.\"]','[1]','easy','[\"Modularization\", \"OOP\"]','https://mitcommlab.mit.edu/broad/commkit/coding-mindset/',0,0,'2025-10-01 11:21:18','2025-10-01 11:21:18','mcq');
INSERT INTO `questions` VALUES ('0b6cad23-e5be-4053-b6f9-b722eab9e5bb','101','4982c0da-e4ec-4bb3-8724-e84f6e4994f4','23d58d77-91d2-49a0-83ea-dde75a5d6df8','Which function name in the code snippet below follows the guideline of naming functions as clear, action-oriented verbs?\n<pre><code>\nfunction processData(data) { /* ... */ }\nfunction dataProcessing(data) { /* ... */ }\n</code></pre>','[\"processData\", \"dataProcessing\", \"handleData\", \"dataHandler\"]','[0]','easy','[\"naming\", \"code style\"]','https://mitcommlab.mit.edu/broad/commkit/coding-and-comment-style/',0,0,'2025-10-01 11:21:18','2025-10-01 11:21:18','mcq');
INSERT INTO `questions` VALUES ('0bee0b0f-ae84-47d1-8e94-e27a9eb43c8b','101','113bba62-604b-430b-a8e5-4605a157a318','066c011c-a649-4957-a54d-1a7cd2d7d7f4','The response “Sorry, I’m not able to provide an answer to that question. [no-context]” primarily indicates which issue?','[\"System hardware failure\", \"Lack of sufficient context\", \"Violation of content policy\", \"User authentication required\"]','[1]','medium','[\"context\", \"interpretation\"]','rag_context',0,0,'2025-09-30 12:18:53','2025-09-30 12:18:53','mcq');
INSERT INTO `questions` VALUES ('0bf4248c-2024-42cb-9be1-bcc0aa5daedf','101','45f977b0-5088-4fb6-b4f7-a680e167e063','3dce6102-6fb1-4295-9cc1-c5066e8f1844','Which of the following git push commands correctly use colon notation to rename or delete remote branches?','[\"git push origin old-branch:new-branch\", \"git push origin :old-branch\", \"git push origin new-branch:new-branch\", \"git push origin main\"]','[0, 1]','easy','[\"git push\", \"branches\"]','Provided Context',0,0,'2025-09-30 14:40:21','2025-09-30 14:40:21','multiple_response');
INSERT INTO `questions` VALUES ('0c5baed3-9e68-4604-bc24-46067fcf8084','101','fff1e95c-c568-4ea4-9eae-ef9918da7474','066c011c-a649-4957-a54d-1a7cd2d7d7f4','According to \'The Case Against Bad Code\', bad code often takes longer to write initially than well-designed code.','[\"True\", \"False\"]','[0]','Medium','[\"Code Quality\", \"Bad Code\"]','https://www.dbswebsite.com/blog/the-case-against-bad-code/',0,0,'2025-09-15 09:33:22','2025-09-15 09:33:22','mcq');
INSERT INTO `questions` VALUES ('0d90c4b4-d315-473f-9fc2-9fefbf2bec9c','101','113bba62-604b-430b-a8e5-4605a157a318','066c011c-a649-4957-a54d-1a7cd2d7d7f4','Bad code:  \n<pre><code>void configure(boolean verbose, boolean debug, boolean optimize) { ... }\n</code></pre>Good code:  \n<pre><code>enum Mode { VERBOSE, DEBUG, OPTIMIZE }\nvoid configure(Mode mode) { ... }\n</code></pre>What principle is applied in the good code?','[\"Parameter object pattern to reduce complexity\", \"Increased verbosity\", \"Looser coupling\", \"Monolithic design\"]','[0]','Medium','[\"Simplification\", \"Parameters\"]','https://blog.codinghorror.com/the-best-code-is-no-code-at-all/',0,0,'2025-09-16 11:18:25','2025-09-16 11:18:25','mcq');
INSERT INTO `questions` VALUES ('0dcdecb5-0993-4fd1-b404-58ca66bf0122','101','4982c0da-e4ec-4bb3-8724-e84f6e4994f4','23d58d77-91d2-49a0-83ea-dde75a5d6df8','Inside a catch block that handles invalid function arguments, which of the following parameter names best eliminates redundancy by leveraging the catch context?','[\"argumentException\", \"invalidArgument\", \"exceptionArgument\", \"argumentError\"]','[1]','easy','[\"context\", \"naming\"]','https://mitcommlab.mit.edu/broad/commkit/coding-and-comment-style/',0,0,'2025-10-01 11:06:01','2025-10-01 11:06:01','mcq');
INSERT INTO `questions` VALUES ('0f0c7397-f011-47c5-bc0a-78a66910241d','user-admin-001','686a9350-c95b-4ab5-9e08-af1d8a335b63','53fa3c1d-50e6-4c78-b322-6488865517d0','Consider the following implementation:\n<pre><code>\ndef factorial(n):\n    if n == 0:\n        return 1\n    else:\n        return n * factorial(n - 1)\n</code></pre>\nWhich of the following best describes Python’s behavior when factorial(-3) is executed?','[\"It returns 1 immediately\", \"It raises a RecursionError indicating maximum recursion depth exceeded\", \"It enters an infinite loop without raising an error\", \"It raises a ValueError because negative inputs are invalid\"]','[1]','hard','[\"recursion\", \"factorial\"]','https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/python/recursion-in-python/',0,0,'2025-10-06 17:40:30','2025-10-06 17:40:30','mcq');
INSERT INTO `questions` VALUES ('109d016f-92b7-47e2-b872-c48ac3aa768b','101','1ae3f056-2a49-4bff-9c8c-5fe084e2d83b','066c011c-a649-4957-a54d-1a7cd2d7d7f4','True or False: Using an unhandled else clause for an unexpected enum value can hide future bugs.\n\nExample:\n<pre><code>from enum import Enum\n\nclass Color(Enum):\n    RED = 1\n    GREEN = 2\n\n\ndef is_primary(color):\n    if color == Color.RED:\n        return True\n    elif color == Color.GREEN:\n        return True\n    else:\n        return False  # hides any new Color variants\n</code></pre>','[\"True\", \"False\"]','[0]','Medium','[\"Enums\", \"Robustness\"]','Good Code, Bad Code -- Tom Long -- Anna’s Archive.pdf (chapter 6.6)“Future-proof enum handling”',0,0,'2025-09-16 11:20:01','2025-09-16 11:20:01','mcq');
INSERT INTO `questions` VALUES ('10a71f64-c900-423c-8eeb-1da6b917bb37','101','22f22cb0-c592-491f-827b-4ef683b97cc1','23d58d77-91d2-49a0-83ea-dde75a5d6df8','You must choose between two sorting algorithms for a collaborative project: Algorithm X is highly optimized for speed but uses complex, deeply nested recursion that future contributors find hard to modify. Algorithm Y is slightly slower but written in a clear, modular style that makes it easy to extend and refactor. According to the three high-level goals of a coding mindset, which goal is best supported by choosing Algorithm Y?','[\"Write code that solves a specific problem\", \"Write code that is easy to read and understand\", \"Write code that is maintainable and extendable\", \"Optimize algorithmic efficiency at all costs\"]','[2]','easy','[\"Algorithm Selection\", \"High-Level Goals\"]','https://mitcommlab.mit.edu/broad/commkit/coding-mindset/',0,0,'2025-10-06 10:47:58','2025-10-06 10:47:58','mcq');
INSERT INTO `questions` VALUES ('113fa4a1-f16f-4004-9df3-b32cc55bb33b','user-admin-001','686a9350-c95b-4ab5-9e08-af1d8a335b63','53fa3c1d-50e6-4c78-b322-6488865517d0','Examine the following code snippet and identify which statements are true regarding variable scope and values:\n<pre><code>\ncount = 5\ndef shadow():\n    count = 10\n    return count\ndef modify():\n    global count\n    count += 3\n    return count\nprint(shadow())\nprint(count)\nprint(modify())\nprint(count)\n</code></pre>\nWhich of the following statements are correct?','[\"shadow() returns 10.\", \"The global variable count remains 5 after calling shadow().\", \"modify() both updates the global count to 8 and returns 8.\", \"Calling modify() creates a new local variable count that does not affect the global variable.\"]','[0, 1, 2]','medium','[\"Variable Scope\", \"Global Variables\", \"Local Variables\"]','https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/python/global-local-variables-python/',0,0,'2025-10-07 15:12:28','2025-10-07 15:12:28','multiple_response');
INSERT INTO `questions` VALUES ('13da7ebe-b0e6-4bf6-912b-18cd4ba3ec97','101','113bba62-604b-430b-a8e5-4605a157a318','066c011c-a649-4957-a54d-1a7cd2d7d7f4','Bad code:  \n<pre><code>void createUser(String name, String email, String password, String address, String phoneNumber) { ... }\n</code></pre>Good code:  \n<pre><code>class UserInfo { ... }\nvoid createUser(UserInfo info) { ... }\n</code></pre>Refactoring to a single UserInfo object improves readability compared to the version with five parameters.','[\"True\", \"False\"]','[0]','Medium','[\"Readability\", \"Parameters\"]','Good Code, Bad Code -- Tom Long -- 1, 2021 -- Manning Publications -- Anna’s Archive.pdf',0,0,'2025-09-16 11:18:25','2025-09-16 11:18:25','mcq');
INSERT INTO `questions` VALUES ('142f1532-5271-494c-864f-380c2bb966f1','101','1ae3f056-2a49-4bff-9c8c-5fe084e2d83b','066c011c-a649-4957-a54d-1a7cd2d7d7f4','True or False: Returning an empty list instead of None when no records are found can prevent unexpected NoneType errors.\n\nBad code:\n<pre><code>def get_users():\n    users = fetch_from_db()\n    if not users:\n        return None\n    return users\n</code></pre>\nGood code:\n<pre><code>def get_users():\n    users = fetch_from_db()\n    return users if users else []\n</code></pre>','[\"True\", \"False\"]','[0]','Medium','[\"Null Object\", \"Error Handling\"]','Good Code, Bad Code -- Tom Long -- Anna’s Archive.pdf (chapter 6.2)“Use the null object pattern appropriately”',0,0,'2025-09-16 11:20:01','2025-09-16 11:20:01','mcq');
INSERT INTO `questions` VALUES ('14c6585c-be3c-4852-afbb-bd7400f0481e','user-admin-001','686a9350-c95b-4ab5-9e08-af1d8a335b63','53fa3c1d-50e6-4c78-b322-6488865517d0','Consider the following Python-like recursive in-order traversal of a binary tree:\n<pre><code>\ndef inorder(node):\n    if node:\n        inorder(node.left)\n        print(node.val)\n        inorder(node.right)\n</code></pre>\nFor a binary tree of height h, which statement correctly describes the additional memory overhead of this recursive traversal compared to an equivalent iterative traversal using an explicit stack?','[\"Recursive uses O(h) call stack frames; iterative uses O(1) extra memory.\", \"Recursive uses O(h) call stack frames; iterative uses O(h) explicit stack entries.\", \"Recursive uses O(n) call stack frames in all cases; iterative uses O(h) explicit stack entries.\", \"Recursive uses O(1) extra memory; iterative uses O(h) explicit stack entries.\"]','[1]','easy','[\"recursion\", \"iteration\", \"binary tree\"]','https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/python/recursion-in-python/',0,0,'2025-10-06 17:36:54','2025-10-06 17:36:54','mcq');
INSERT INTO `questions` VALUES ('14d5e51e-4024-4ba0-a6fc-e2f46abffc1e','101','4982c0da-e4ec-4bb3-8724-e84f6e4994f4','23d58d77-91d2-49a0-83ea-dde75a5d6df8','Which of the following are components of the coding mindset framework for balancing the three high-level goals in programming decisions?','[\"Always choose the most technically sophisticated solution regardless of other factors.\", \"Evaluate whether your chosen solution satisfies the goals of solving the specific problem, readability, and maintainability.\", \"If all three high-level goals cannot be met, ask which one or two goals are most important for you and your collaborators.\", \"Always prioritize performance over readability.\"]','[1, 2]','easy','[\"Coding Mindset\", \"High-Level Goals\"]','https://mitcommlab.mit.edu/broad/commkit/coding-mindset/',0,0,'2025-10-01 10:58:27','2025-10-01 10:58:27','multiple_response');
