INSERT INTO `questions` VALUES ('8ab36acd-ff5b-4c23-9792-d445773f0a04','101','6d1a9f63-ca33-415f-9e21-5b4275c94872','bed2fd2f-7387-4949-82c1-d3a1fc2a53ce','Which of the following features describe the Mice Drawer System (MDS) used for the 91-day space endurance experiment aboard the ISS?','[\"Food supply was fully automatic for 60 days but eventually required manual advancement by the crew.\", \"Water reservoirs needed manual refilling roughly every 10 days during the mission.\", \"The habitat design was entirely autonomous with no need for astronaut intervention in 91 days.\", \"Only six mice could be housed in the MDS, including three transgenic and three wild-type mice.\"]','[0, 1, 3]','easy','[\"MDS\", \"space endurance\"]','Document Chunk 2',0,0,'2025-10-06 12:26:49','2025-10-06 12:26:49','multiple_response');
INSERT INTO `questions` VALUES ('8abf9be8-d5fa-4771-8033-561b88aaa0bf','101','1ae3f056-2a49-4bff-9c8c-5fe084e2d83b','066c011c-a649-4957-a54d-1a7cd2d7d7f4','Consider the following Python functions:\nBad code:\n<pre><code>def calc(x, y):\n    return x + y\n</code></pre>\nGood code:\n<pre><code>def calculate_total_price(item_price, tax_rate):\n    return item_price + item_price * tax_rate\n</code></pre>\nWhich of the following best describes why the good code is more readable?','[\"It uses fewer lines of code\", \"It uses more generic variable names\", \"The parameter names reveal their purpose\", \"It avoids arithmetic operations\"]','[2]','Medium','[\"Naming\", \"Readability\"]','Good Code, Bad Code -- Tom Long -- Anna’s Archive.pdf (chapter 5.1)“Use descriptive names”',0,0,'2025-09-16 11:20:01','2025-09-16 11:20:01','mcq');
INSERT INTO `questions` VALUES ('8cb89871-4eb2-4614-a42f-010875dd0e59','user-admin-001','686a9350-c95b-4ab5-9e08-af1d8a335b63','53fa3c1d-50e6-4c78-b322-6488865517d0','Consider the following Python-like implementation of merge sort:\n<pre><code>// arr is a list of numbers\ndef merge_sort(arr):\n    if len(arr) <= 1:\n        return arr\n    mid = len(arr) // 2\n    left = merge_sort(arr[:mid])\n    right = merge_sort(arr[mid:])\n    return merge(left, right)\n</code></pre>\nWhen merge_sort is invoked on a list of length 8, how many total calls to merge_sort (including the initial call and all recursive calls) occur?','[\"8\", \"12\", \"15\", \"16\"]','[2]','hard','[\"divide-and-conquer\", \"recursion\"]','https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/python/recursion-in-python/',0,0,'2025-10-06 17:40:30','2025-10-06 17:40:30','mcq');
INSERT INTO `questions` VALUES ('8d22c661-2fcd-43bf-bc57-f70574b67cf8','101','4982c0da-e4ec-4bb3-8724-e84f6e4994f4','23d58d77-91d2-49a0-83ea-dde75a5d6df8','Consider the following code snippet:\n\n<pre><code>\n// Python-like pseudocode\nbuffer = []\ndef process(data):\n    for item in data:\n        buffer.append(transform(item))\n    return buffer\n</code></pre>\n\nWhich refactoring best restricts the scope of `buffer` to enhance data locality?','[\"Move the declaration of `buffer` inside the `process` function.\", \"Keep `buffer` at the module level to reuse it across calls.\", \"Pass `buffer` as a parameter to the `process` function.\", \"Define `buffer` as a global constant.\"]','[0]','easy','[\"Data Localization\", \"Modularization\"]','https://mitcommlab.mit.edu/broad/commkit/coding-mindset/',0,0,'2025-10-01 11:21:18','2025-10-01 11:21:18','mcq');
INSERT INTO `questions` VALUES ('8d319fab-64be-4429-a49f-0d1f946ad895','user-admin-001','686a9350-c95b-4ab5-9e08-af1d8a335b63','53fa3c1d-50e6-4c78-b322-6488865517d0','Consider the following Python code snippet:\n<pre><code>\ndef foo(a, b, *args, **kwargs):\n    print(a, b)\n    print(args)\n    print(kwargs)\n\nparams = [1, 2, 3, 4]\noptions = {\'x\': 100, \'y\': 200}\nfoo(*params, **options)\n</code></pre>\nWhat is the output of this code?','[\"1 2\\n(3, 4)\\n{\'x\': 100, \'y\': 200}\", \"1 2 3 4\\n{\'x\': 100, \'y\': 200}\", \"1\\n2\\n[3, 4]\\n{\'x\': 100, \'y\': 200}\", \"A SyntaxError is raised\"]','[0]','easy','[\"*args\", \"**kwargs\"]','https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/python/python-functions/',0,0,'2025-10-07 15:53:46','2025-10-07 15:53:46','mcq');
INSERT INTO `questions` VALUES ('8d716b3b-3593-4caf-8177-bae2851747fd','user-admin-001','1f9f921d-8a65-4a6e-9b74-96a6979da10b','8cceadf0-de0e-430d-a195-50d9d961ce79','Given the following pseudo-code illustrating an Active Object with recursive method invocations and futures:\n<pre><code>\nservice = Service()\nfuture = service.process(3)\nprint(future.get())\nclass Service(ActiveObject):\n    def process(self, n):\n        if n == 0:\n            return Future(1)\n        f = self.process(n - 1)\n        return Future(lambda: f.get() * n)\n</code></pre>\nWhat is the most likely outcome when this code is executed?','[\"It correctly prints the factorial result: 6\", \"It deadlocks because the worker thread blocks on a future that it must itself resolve\", \"It throws a runtime exception due to a circular future dependency\", \"It prints a Future object reference instead of a numeric value\"]','[1]','hard','[\"Active Object\", \"Concurrency\"]','https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Software_design_pattern',0,0,'2025-10-08 21:53:59','2025-10-08 21:53:59','mcq');
INSERT INTO `questions` VALUES ('8eda6009-947f-43b6-99e5-534729eb0e29','user-admin-001','686a9350-c95b-4ab5-9e08-af1d8a335b63','53fa3c1d-50e6-4c78-b322-6488865517d0','Consider the following function definition and call:\n<pre><code>def func(a, b=2, *args, c=5, **kwargs):\n    print(a, b, args, c, kwargs)\n\nfunc(1, 3, 4, 5, d=7, c=6, e=8)\n</code></pre>\nHow does Python bind the arguments, and what will be printed?','[\"1 3 (4, 5) 6 {\'d\': 7, \'e\': 8}\", \"1 3 (4, 5) 5 {\'d\': 7, \'e\': 8, \'c\': 6}\", \"1 2 (3, 4, 5) 6 {\'d\': 7, \'e\': 8}\", \"1 2 (3, 4, 5) 5 {\'d\': 7, \'e\': 8}\"]','[0]','Hard','[\"args\", \"kwargs\"]','https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/python/python-functions/',0,0,'2025-10-07 14:05:29','2025-10-07 14:05:29','mcq');
INSERT INTO `questions` VALUES ('8ef46e33-b00b-42f6-9813-6cd049d1fdd3','101','80e9258e-0884-4728-97eb-b5381527a0a7','066c011c-a649-4957-a54d-1a7cd2d7d7f4','Consider the following two Java snippets that read lines from a file:\n\nSnippet A:\n<pre><code>BufferedReader reader = new BufferedReader(new FileReader(file));\nString text = \"\";\nString line;\nwhile ((line = reader.readLine()) != null) {\n    text = text + line;\n}\n</code></pre>\n\nSnippet B:\n<pre><code>BufferedReader reader = new BufferedReader(new FileReader(file));\nStringBuilder builder = new StringBuilder();\nString line;\nwhile ((line = reader.readLine()) != null) {\n    builder.append(line);\n}\nString text = builder.toString();\n</code></pre>\n\nWhich snippet demonstrates better performance and why?','[\"Snippet A is better because it uses immutable strings.\", \"Snippet B is better because StringBuilder reduces time complexity to linear.\", \"Snippet A is better because concatenation is just as fast.\", \"Snippet B is worse because it uses more memory.\"]','[1]','Medium','[\"Performance\", \"Java\"]','http://varianceexplained.org/programming/bad-code/',1,0,'2025-09-15 20:33:44','2025-09-15 20:33:44','mcq');
INSERT INTO `questions` VALUES ('8f762467-c48e-4539-afce-28a058a526d1','user-admin-001','87587b16-87be-44d5-b88e-8f0fb54f586b','6c68a915-6bd2-4a98-a9f0-6f76e55889d1','Consider the following JavaScript-like snippet:\n<pre><code>\n// each line on its own line\nfunction greet() {\n  console.log(\"Hi\");\n    console.log(\"there\");\n}\n</code></pre>\nWhat style violation will a linter configured for consistent indentation most likely flag?','[\"Inconsistent indentation on the third line\", \"Missing semicolon at the end of a statement\", \"Incorrect function naming convention\", \"Unused variable declaration\"]','[0]','easy','[\"linting\", \"indentation\"]','https://medium.com/geekculture/what-is-a-good-code-and-why-is-it-all-about-others-not-ourselves-40730c7a03e5',0,0,'2025-10-08 11:20:17','2025-10-08 11:20:17','mcq');
INSERT INTO `questions` VALUES ('908fb7d5-bd5d-4468-8bef-371cd7449f92','101','4982c0da-e4ec-4bb3-8724-e84f6e4994f4','23d58d77-91d2-49a0-83ea-dde75a5d6df8','According to the coding mindset framework, which of the following are the three high-level goals of a programmer? (Select all that apply)','[\"Write code that solves a specific problem\", \"Write code that is easy to read and understand\", \"Write code that minimizes runtime through advanced optimizations\", \"Write code that is maintainable and extendable\"]','[0, 1, 3]','easy','[\"Three High-Level Goals\", \"Coding Mindset\"]','MIT CommLab Coding Mindset',0,0,'2025-10-01 11:04:46','2025-10-01 11:04:46','multiple_response');
INSERT INTO `questions` VALUES ('90a76c9a-0763-49ff-8469-de712105d189','101','4982c0da-e4ec-4bb3-8724-e84f6e4994f4','23d58d77-91d2-49a0-83ea-dde75a5d6df8','Which of the following naming examples leverage context to avoid redundancy in code names?','[\"catch(Exception argumentException) { /* handle error */ }\", \"catch(Exception invalidArgument) { /* handle error */ }\", \"catch(Exception argumentDimensionMismatch) { /* handle dimension mismatch */ }\", \"Within a CustomerService class, naming a member variable as \'data\' instead of \'customerData\'\"]','[1, 2, 3]','easy','[\"context\", \"naming\"]','Document Chunk 2',0,0,'2025-10-01 11:04:46','2025-10-01 11:04:46','multiple_response');
INSERT INTO `questions` VALUES ('90bcdb11-aa60-4c1d-92e9-f557fb9dce07','101','fff1e95c-c568-4ea4-9eae-ef9918da7474','066c011c-a649-4957-a54d-1a7cd2d7d7f4','Review this Java code for reading a file:\n<pre><code>BufferedReader reader = new BufferedReader(new FileReader(file));\nString line = null;\nString text = \"\";\nwhile ((line = reader.readLine()) != null) {\n  text = text + line;\n}\n</code></pre>\nWhich modification would most improve performance when processing large files?','[\"Use recursion instead of loops\", \"Replace String concatenation with StringBuilder\", \"Read the file character by character\", \"Use a Vector collection instead of String\"]','[1]','Medium','[\"Performance\", \"Java\"]','https://varianceexplained.org/programming/bad-code/',0,0,'2025-09-15 09:24:36','2025-09-15 09:24:36','mcq');
INSERT INTO `questions` VALUES ('91318a57-d75f-444a-a87c-f28bbdb2dfa4','user-admin-001','686a9350-c95b-4ab5-9e08-af1d8a335b63','53fa3c1d-50e6-4c78-b322-6488865517d0','Examine the following function that uses *args and **kwargs for flexible inputs:\n<pre><code>\ndef summarize(title, *args, **kwargs):\n    total = sum(args)\n    return f\"{title}: {total} ({\', \'.join(f\'{k}={v}\' for k, v in kwargs.items())})\"\n</code></pre>\nWhat is true when calling summarize(\"Sales\", 10, 20, 30, region=\"North\", year=2021)?','[\"Inside summarize, args is a tuple containing the values (10, 20, 30).\", \"Inside summarize, kwargs is a dict containing {\'region\': \'North\', \'year\': 2021}.\", \"The function call will return \\\"Sales: 2021 (region=North, year=2021)\\\".\", \"The parameter title captures the first positional argument \\\"Sales\\\".\"]','[0, 1, 3]','medium','[\"args_kwargs\", \"variadic parameters\"]','https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/python/python-functions/',0,0,'2025-10-07 15:10:29','2025-10-07 15:10:29','multiple_response');
INSERT INTO `questions` VALUES ('92876b72-8476-43c1-8530-35c4ab405850','101','1ae3f056-2a49-4bff-9c8c-5fe084e2d83b','066c011c-a649-4957-a54d-1a7cd2d7d7f4','Compare these two implementations:\nBad code:\n<pre><code>def process(text):\n    cleaned = text.strip().lower()\n    words = cleaned.split(\' \')\n    freq = {}\n    for w in words:\n        freq[w] = freq.get(w, 0) + 1\n    return freq\n</code></pre>\nGood code:\n<pre><code>def split_words(text):\n    return text.strip().lower().split()\n\ndef word_frequencies(words):\n    freq = {}\n    for w in words:\n        freq[w] = freq.get(w, 0) + 1\n    return freq\n\n# usage:\ntext = \'Hello world hello\'\nwords = split_words(text)\nfreq = word_frequencies(words)\n</code></pre>\nWhich benefit does the good code demonstrate?','[\"More nested logic\", \"Better layering via single-responsibility functions\", \"Less total lines\", \"It hides errors\"]','[1]','Medium','[\"Abstraction\", \"Functions\"]','Good Code, Bad Code -- Tom Long -- Anna’s Archive.pdf (chapter 2.3.2)“Functions”',0,0,'2025-09-16 11:20:01','2025-09-16 11:20:01','mcq');
INSERT INTO `questions` VALUES ('963f41d4-c5d7-483d-a10d-ff36c97350bd','101','4982c0da-e4ec-4bb3-8724-e84f6e4994f4','23d58d77-91d2-49a0-83ea-dde75a5d6df8','You decide to use bubble sort to sort a list that is already nearly sorted, rather than a more efficient algorithm like quicksort. According to best practices for inline comments, which of the following comments best explains this non-obvious implementation choice?','[\"// Using bubble sort here because it performs better on nearly sorted lists, avoiding quicksort\'s overhead\", \"// Sort the list using bubble sort\", \"// bubbleSort is simpler to implement\", \"// For more details on sorting, see the sorting algorithms documentation\"]','[0]','easy','[\"comments\", \"code style\"]','https://mitcommlab.mit.edu/broad/commkit/coding-mindset/',0,0,'2025-10-01 11:06:01','2025-10-01 11:06:01','mcq');
INSERT INTO `questions` VALUES ('9642a3cc-84d6-47d4-bb19-4040995e6f16','user-admin-001','1f9f921d-8a65-4a6e-9b74-96a6979da10b','8cceadf0-de0e-430d-a195-50d9d961ce79','You are modeling the Strategy pattern with UML. The class diagram defines Context with an attribute «strategy»:Strategy and operation contextInterface(), plus a setter setStrategy(s:Strategy). Strategy is an interface with operation algorithmInterface(), and ConcreteStrategyA/B implement it. The sequence diagram shows Client→Context:setStrategy(new ConcreteStrategyA), Client→Context:contextInterface(), Context→ConcreteStrategyA:algorithmInterface().\n\nWhich modeling choices correctly decouple Context from concrete algorithms and support adding new strategies without modifying Context?','[\"Use a composition (filled diamond) from Context to Strategy in the class diagram, and in the sequence diagram draw the call from Context directly to the ConcreteStrategy lifeline.\", \"Use an aggregation (open diamond) from Context to the Strategy interface in the class diagram, and in the sequence diagram direct the algorithmInterface() message from Context to the Strategy lifeline (typed «interface»), not to a concrete class.\", \"Use only a dependency (dashed arrow) from Context to Strategy in the class diagram, and in the sequence diagram show Context creating new ConcreteStrategy instances internally before calling algorithmInterface().\", \"Model Strategy as an abstract class with generalization arrows to ConcreteStrategy, and in the sequence diagram target algorithmInterface() calls directly to each ConcreteStrategy lifeline rather than through the interface.\"]','[1]','hard','[\"strategy\", \"uml\"]','https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Strategy_pattern',0,0,'2025-10-08 21:53:59','2025-10-08 21:53:59','mcq');
INSERT INTO `questions` VALUES ('97f21dbd-4587-4793-a820-37acf654eead','101','fff1e95c-c568-4ea4-9eae-ef9918da7474','066c011c-a649-4957-a54d-1a7cd2d7d7f4','Examine the following code snippet:\n<pre><code>\nBufferedReader reader = new BufferedReader(new FileReader(file));\nString line = null;\nString text = \"\";\nwhile ((line = reader.readLine()) != null) {\n    text = text + line;\n}\n</code></pre>\nWhat is the primary performance issue with this approach?','[\"Repeated string concatenation in a loop\", \"Using BufferedReader instead of FileInputStream\", \"Reading line by line instead of byte blocks\", \"Not closing the reader\"]','[0]','Medium','[\"Java\", \"Performance\"]','http://varianceexplained.org/programming/bad-code/',0,0,'2025-09-15 09:33:22','2025-09-15 09:33:22','mcq');
INSERT INTO `questions` VALUES ('98b490ac-da31-4210-9095-2b936603c8bc','user-admin-001','87587b16-87be-44d5-b88e-8f0fb54f586b','6c68a915-6bd2-4a98-a9f0-6f76e55889d1','In the following JSDoc-annotated code snippet, which command-line tool would you use to auto-generate API documentation from these comments?\n\n<pre><code>\n// Adds two numbers.\n/**\n * @param {number} x - First number.\n * @param {number} y - Second number.\n * @returns {number} Sum of x and y.\n */\nfunction sum(x, y) {\n  return x + y;\n}\n</code></pre>','[\"jsdoc\", \"eslint\", \"typedoc\", \"prettier\"]','[0]','easy','[\"jsdoc\", \"documentation\"]','https://medium.com/geekculture/what-is-a-good-code-and-why-is-it-all-about-others-not-ourselves-40730c7a03e5',0,0,'2025-10-08 11:20:17','2025-10-08 11:20:17','mcq');
