INSERT INTO `questions` VALUES ('a115371c-a2ad-4515-92b7-d4dc1bfa5732','101','1ae3f056-2a49-4bff-9c8c-5fe084e2d83b','066c011c-a649-4957-a54d-1a7cd2d7d7f4','Which approach better represents a timestamp and allows rich date/time operations?\nBad code:\n<pre><code>def get_current_time():\n    return int(time.time())\n</code></pre>\nGood code:\n<pre><code>from datetime import datetime\n\ndef get_current_time():\n    return datetime.utcnow()\n</code></pre>','[\"Bad code – using int timestamp\", \"Good code – using datetime object\", \"Both are equivalent\", \"Use string instead\"]','[1]','Medium','[\"Time\", \"Data Types\"]','Good Code, Bad Code -- Tom Long -- Anna’s Archive.pdf (chapter 7.4)“Dealing with time”',0,0,'2025-09-16 11:20:01','2025-09-16 11:20:01','mcq');
INSERT INTO `questions` VALUES ('a1338b86-dc2f-40ed-9e5a-23d55d0099b3','101','113bba62-604b-430b-a8e5-4605a157a318','066c011c-a649-4957-a54d-1a7cd2d7d7f4','Bad code:  \n<pre><code>class UserService {\n  void register(User u) {\n    Connection c = DriverManager.getConnection(...);\n    // business logic\n    // logging to file\n    c.close();\n  }\n}\n</code></pre>Good code:  \n<pre><code>class UserService {\n  private final UserRepository repo;\n  private final Logger logger;\n  UserService(UserRepository repo, Logger logger) { ... }\n  void register(User u) {\n    repo.save(u);\n    logger.info(\"User saved\");\n  }\n}\n</code></pre>Which cohesion type does the good design demonstrate?','[\"Functional cohesion\", \"Sequential cohesion\", \"Coincidental cohesion\", \"Temporal cohesion\"]','[0]','Medium','[\"Cohesion\", \"Classes\"]','Good Code, Bad Code -- Tom Long -- 1, 2021 -- Manning Publications -- Anna’s Archive.pdf',0,0,'2025-09-16 11:18:25','2025-09-16 11:18:25','mcq');
INSERT INTO `questions` VALUES ('a4078383-00c3-4e85-8466-5cb10861643a','101','fff1e95c-c568-4ea4-9eae-ef9918da7474','066c011c-a649-4957-a54d-1a7cd2d7d7f4','Which benefit is most directly achieved by adopting Test-Driven Development (TDD)?','[\"Increased code verbosity\", \"Early detection of defects through automated tests\", \"Fewer test cases\", \"Reduced modularity\"]','[1]','Medium','[\"TDD\", \"Testing\"]','https://blog.rarecrew.com/post/good-code-vs-bad-code',0,0,'2025-09-15 09:24:36','2025-09-15 09:24:36','mcq');
INSERT INTO `questions` VALUES ('a43932aa-0314-426a-9b9a-bea74bd2d352','101','4982c0da-e4ec-4bb3-8724-e84f6e4994f4','23d58d77-91d2-49a0-83ea-dde75a5d6df8','A data scientist is starting a new analysis project and wants to follow best practices for separation of concerns and ensure that collaborators can run their code without path errors. Which directory structure and file referencing approach should they choose?','[\"Create separate folders such as data/raw, data/processed, src, and results, and write code that reads files using relative paths like \\\"../data/raw/experiment.csv\\\".\", \"Place all data files and scripts in a single folder, prefix file names with \'raw_\' and \'processed_\', and refer to files using absolute paths from C:\\\\Users to ensure clarity.\", \"Use individual folders for data, scripts, and results but hard-code absolute file paths in each script so it directly points to files on the developer’s machine.\", \"Organize files solely by date in nested date-named folders under a top-level \'archive\' folder, and reference files using relative paths deep in the folder hierarchy.\"]','[0]','easy','[\"File Structure\", \"Relative Paths\"]','https://mitcommlab.mit.edu/broad/commkit/file-structure/',0,0,'2025-10-01 11:09:53','2025-10-01 11:09:53','mcq');
INSERT INTO `questions` VALUES ('a5c2cd8c-e19b-44f4-b19e-d4b5f2691f17','user-admin-001','686a9350-c95b-4ab5-9e08-af1d8a335b63','53fa3c1d-50e6-4c78-b322-6488865517d0','Examine the following function definition:\n<pre><code>\ndef categorize(x):\n    if x > 0:\n        return x\n    elif x == 0:\n        return\n    return x, -x\n</code></pre>\nWhich of the following statements about calls to categorize are correct? Select all that apply.','[\"categorize(5) returns the integer 5\", \"categorize(0) returns None\", \"categorize(-3) returns a tuple containing two values\", \"type(categorize(0)) is tuple\"]','[0, 1, 2]','medium','[\"Return Statement\", \"Functions\"]','https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/python/python-functions/',0,0,'2025-10-07 15:12:28','2025-10-07 15:12:28','multiple_response');
INSERT INTO `questions` VALUES ('a73e9fd5-a7ea-49ca-9cda-c5cf01610080','101','4982c0da-e4ec-4bb3-8724-e84f6e4994f4','23d58d77-91d2-49a0-83ea-dde75a5d6df8','Which of the following are recommended strategies for writing code that initially solves a specific problem before extending it to address similar problems?','[\"Articulate a clear description of the specific problem before coding\", \"Begin documentation or the README with a concise problem description\", \"Identify and modularize components that may be reused to address similar problems\", \"Write code that immediately handles a wide range of different problems to avoid future extensions\"]','[0, 1, 2]','easy','[\"Modularization\", \"Documentation\"]','Coding Mindset Article',0,0,'2025-10-01 10:58:27','2025-10-01 10:58:27','multiple_response');
INSERT INTO `questions` VALUES ('a8160051-4da2-41c1-a042-3561fdc74ce3','101','4982c0da-e4ec-4bb3-8724-e84f6e4994f4','23d58d77-91d2-49a0-83ea-dde75a5d6df8','Given the code below that sorts an almost-sorted list:\n<pre><code>\n// Assume data_list is almost sorted with new items appended\nfor i in range(len(data_list)):\n    for j in range(0, len(data_list)-i-1):\n        if data_list[j] > data_list[j+1]:\n            data_list[j], data_list[j+1] = data_list[j+1], data_list[j]\n</code></pre>\nWhich comment best follows the guideline of explaining a non-obvious algorithmic choice?','[\"// Use bubble sort to sort the list\", \"// Bubble sort because it’s easy to implement\", \"// Bubble sort is efficient for nearly-sorted lists, as here\", \"// Quicksort omitted due to average-case complexity\"]','[2]','easy','[\"comments\", \"algorithms\"]','https://mitcommlab.mit.edu/broad/commkit/coding-mindset/',0,0,'2025-10-01 11:21:18','2025-10-01 11:21:18','mcq');
INSERT INTO `questions` VALUES ('a8690dcf-e329-4863-88cb-07eea4c39cb0','101','113bba62-604b-430b-a8e5-4605a157a318','066c011c-a649-4957-a54d-1a7cd2d7d7f4','Bad code:  \n<pre><code>String text = \"\";\nwhile ((line = reader.readLine()) != null) {\n  text = text + line;\n}\n</code></pre>Good code:  \n<pre><code>StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder();\nwhile ((line = reader.readLine()) != null) {\n  sb.append(line);\n}\nString text = sb.toString();\n</code></pre>Which principle does the good code demonstrate?','[\"Testability\", \"Performance and efficiency\", \"Security\", \"Abstraction\"]','[1]','Medium','[\"Performance\", \"BadCode\"]','http://varianceexplained.org/programming/bad-code/',0,0,'2025-09-16 11:18:25','2025-09-16 11:18:25','mcq');
INSERT INTO `questions` VALUES ('a8ebc8c4-4462-49de-aa11-8e4b446d2f64','101','fff1e95c-c568-4ea4-9eae-ef9918da7474','066c011c-a649-4957-a54d-1a7cd2d7d7f4','Consider this condensed JavaScript implementation:\n<pre><code>var fizzBuzz = function(n) {\n  var o = [];\n  for (let c = 1; c <= n; c++) {\n    o.push(c % 15 == 0 ? \"FizzBuzz\" : c % 3 == 0 ? \"Fizz\" : c % 5 == 0 ? \"Buzz\" : c.toString());\n  }\n  return o;\n};\nWhat is the primary drawback of this implementation?','[\"It is not DRY\", \"It uses deprecated syntax\", \"It is hard to read due to nested ternary operators\", \"It lacks comments\"]','[2]','Medium','[\"Readability\", \"Ternary\"]','https://blog.pragmaticengineer.com/bad-code/',0,0,'2025-09-15 09:24:36','2025-09-15 09:24:36','mcq');
INSERT INTO `questions` VALUES ('aa912395-d571-41a7-9b69-2d5fa770d38a','user-admin-001','87587b16-87be-44d5-b88e-8f0fb54f586b','6c68a915-6bd2-4a98-a9f0-6f76e55889d1','Consider the following code snippet:\n<pre><code>\n// Duplicated discount logic using magic number\nif (customer.isLoyal()) {\n    total -= total * 0.1;\n}\n// ...\nif (user.subscribe == true) {\n    total -= total * 0.1;\n}\n</code></pre>\nRefactoring by extracting the magic number into a named constant and consolidating the duplicated logic into a single helper function are both valid steps to eliminate these code smells and improve maintainability.','[\"True\", \"False\"]','[0]','medium','[\"Refactoring\", \"CodeSmells\"]','SignsOfBadCode',0,0,'2025-10-08 11:22:09','2025-10-08 11:22:09','true_false');
INSERT INTO `questions` VALUES ('abac8b83-dca7-443c-bebe-6f03b02537ae','101','4982c0da-e4ec-4bb3-8724-e84f6e4994f4','23d58d77-91d2-49a0-83ea-dde75a5d6df8','Which statement best describes Python docstrings?','[\"Inline comments explaining non-obvious programming choices inside function bodies.\", \"Special string literals placed immediately after a function, class, or module declaration that describe its purpose.\", \"External documentation files linked to Python modules via configuration.\", \"Compiler directives embedded in code to optimize execution.\"]','[1]','easy','[\"docstrings\", \"Python\"]','https://mitcommlab.mit.edu/broad/commkit/coding-and-comment-style/',0,0,'2025-10-01 10:33:05','2025-10-01 10:33:05','mcq');
INSERT INTO `questions` VALUES ('acb3c8c5-552e-47a7-95be-e4775cfd2315','user-admin-001','686a9350-c95b-4ab5-9e08-af1d8a335b63','53fa3c1d-50e6-4c78-b322-6488865517d0','Consider the following Python functions:\n<pre><code>\ndef tail_fact(n, acc=1):\n    if n == 0:\n        return acc\n    else:\n        return tail_fact(n-1, acc * n)\n\ndef nontail_fact(n):\n    if n == 1:\n        return 1\n    else:\n        return n * nontail_fact(n-1)\n</code></pre>\nTrue or False: tail_fact is tail-recursive and can be optimized into an iterative loop by languages supporting tail-call optimization, whereas nontail_fact is non-tail-recursive and cannot be optimized in that way.','[\"True\", \"False\"]','[0]','easy','[\"tail-recursion\", \"optimization\"]','https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/python/recursion-in-python/',0,0,'2025-10-07 16:04:16','2025-10-07 16:04:16','true_false');
INSERT INTO `questions` VALUES ('ae895fa7-9db5-4970-8c43-e75fb744ae62','101','6d1a9f63-ca33-415f-9e21-5b4275c94872','bed2fd2f-7387-4949-82c1-d3a1fc2a53ce','In the Bion-M 1 study, male C57/BL6 mice were adapted to a space-style paste diet and showed altered water intake and urine output. Researchers normalized urine output to 10 g body weight using this illustrative code:\n\n<pre><code>\n// Calculate urine output per 10 g BW\nnormalized_output = urine_ml / (body_weight_g / 10)\n</code></pre>\n\nWhich of the following quantitative findings were reported for mice on the paste diet? (Select all that apply.)','[\"Normalized urine volume was approximately 2.4 ml per 10 g BW, about tenfold higher than in mice on standard diet\", \"Water intake via the paste diet averaged ~4.25 g per 10 g BW, roughly three times ad libitum consumption\", \"Dry weight of paste food consumed per 10 g BW remained statistically similar to pelleted food at ~1.27 g\", \"Mice on the paste diet produced urine that was more concentrated than on the standard diet\"]','[0, 1, 2]','easy','[\"urine output\", \"paste diet\"]','PMC4136787',0,0,'2025-10-06 12:26:49','2025-10-06 12:26:49','multiple_response');
INSERT INTO `questions` VALUES ('b0407a60-3433-44ee-b985-690d9d6f77ff','user-admin-001','686a9350-c95b-4ab5-9e08-af1d8a335b63','53fa3c1d-50e6-4c78-b322-6488865517d0','Consider the following Python function definition:\n<pre><code>\ndef log(message, level=\'INFO\', user=None):\n    return f\"[{level}] ({user}): {message}\"\n</code></pre>\nWhich of the following calls will execute without a SyntaxError or TypeError? Select all that apply.','[\"log(\\\"System rebooted\\\")\", \"log(\\\"Disk full\\\", user=\\\"admin\\\")\", \"log(level=\\\"ERROR\\\", \\\"Invalid input\\\")\", \"log(user=\\\"guest\\\", \\\"Login successful\\\")\"]','[0, 1]','medium','[\"invocation syntax\", \"default arguments\"]','https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/python/python-functions/',0,0,'2025-10-07 15:12:28','2025-10-07 15:12:28','multiple_response');
INSERT INTO `questions` VALUES ('b260086c-67aa-4e32-b1b5-5ab3447b62d4','user-admin-001','686a9350-c95b-4ab5-9e08-af1d8a335b63','53fa3c1d-50e6-4c78-b322-6488865517d0','Consider the following code snippet:\n<pre><code>\ndef nontail_fact(n):\n    if n == 1:\n        return 1\n    return n * nontail_fact(n-1)\n\ndef tail_fact(n, acc=1):\n    if n == 0:\n        return acc\n    return tail_fact(n-1, acc*n)\n\n# Assume these calls are made from the top-level script\nnontail_fact(4)\ntail_fact(4)\n</code></pre>\nWhich statement best describes the Python call stack behavior during execution of both functions when computing factorial of 4?','[\"At maximum recursion depth, nontail_fact has four active recursive frames, and tail_fact has five active recursive frames (Python does not optimize tail calls).\", \"Both nontail_fact and tail_fact have exactly four active frames at maximum recursion depth because they both decrement n until the base case.\", \"tail_fact has fewer active frames than nontail_fact at maximum recursion depth because its accumulator allows in-place computation.\", \"Python automatically converts tail recursion to iteration, so tail_fact uses only two frames regardless of input size.\"]','[0]','hard','[\"recursion\", \"call stack\"]','https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/python/recursion-in-python/',0,0,'2025-10-06 17:40:30','2025-10-06 17:40:30','mcq');
