INSERT INTO `questions` VALUES ('d2480463-071d-4bb8-a64f-7e632aa41b6a','user-admin-001','87587b16-87be-44d5-b88e-8f0fb54f586b','6c68a915-6bd2-4a98-a9f0-6f76e55889d1','Consider the following code snippet:\n<pre><code>\ndef add_item(cart, item):\n    cart.items.append(item)\n    save_cart(cart)\n    notify_user(cart.user, \"Cart updated.\")\n\ndef remove_item(cart, item):\n    cart.items.remove(item)\n    save_cart(cart)\n    notify_user(cart.user, \"Cart updated.\")\n</code></pre>\nWhich refactoring best applies the DRY principle to eliminate the duplicated save and notify logic?','[\"Extract the save_cart and notify_user calls into a new helper function update_cart(cart) and call it from both add_item and remove_item.\", \"Merge add_item and remove_item into a single function that uses a mode flag to decide whether to append or remove.\", \"Move save_cart and notify_user calls inside the cart.items list methods by modifying the list class.\", \"Keep duplicating the save and notify calls in any new functions to preserve clarity.\"]','[0]','easy','[\"DRY\", \"refactoring\"]','https://blog.bytebytego.com/p/good-code-vs-bad-code',0,0,'2025-10-08 11:20:17','2025-10-08 11:20:17','mcq');
